05775nam a22008415i 9780231550635DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315506357 a10.7312/pass194062doi  a(DE-B1597)566421  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0260302bisacsh04a307.1/21609747232231 aPassell, Aaron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPreserving Neighborhoods :bHow Urban Policy and Community Strategy Shape Baltimore and Brooklyn /cAaron Passell. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b21 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction -- t2 Explaining Change in Baltimore’s Historic Neighborhoods -- t3 Mitigating Gentrification Through Preservation in Central Brooklyn -- t4 Vacancy, Abandonment, Demolition by Neglect, and Project CORE in Baltimore -- t5 Struggling to Preserve in the Context of Aggressive Development Pressure -- t6 Conclusion -- tAppendix: Data, Methods, and Measures -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHistoric preservation is typically regarded as an elitist practice. In this view, designating a neighborhood as historic is a project by and for affluent residents concerned with aesthetics, not affordability. It leads to gentrification and rising property values for wealthy homeowners, while displacement afflicts longer-term, lower-income residents of the neighborhood, often people of color.Through rich case studies of Baltimore and Brooklyn, Aaron Passell complicates this story, exploring how community activists and local governments use historic preservation to accelerate or slow down neighborhood change. He argues that this form of regulation is one of the few remaining urban policy interventions that enable communities to exercise some control over the changing built environments of their neighborhoods. In Baltimore, it is part of a primarily top-down strategy for channeling investment into historic neighborhoods, many of them plagued by vacancy and abandonment. In central Brooklyn, neighborhood groups have discovered the utility of landmark district designation as they seek to mitigate rapid change with whatever legal tools they can. The contrast between Baltimore and Brooklyn reveals that the relationship between historic preservation and neighborhood change varies not only from city to city, but even from neighborhood to neighborhood. In speaking with local activists, Passell finds that historic district designation and enforcement efforts can be a part of neighborhood community building and bottom-up revitalization.Featuring compelling narrative interviews alongside quantitative data, Preserving Neighborhoods is a nuanced mixed-methods study of an important local-level urban policy and its surprisingly varied consequences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCity planningzMarylandzBaltimore. 0aCity planningzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aHistoric districtszMarylandzBaltimore. 0aHistoric districtszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aHistoric preservationxSocial aspectszMarylandzBaltimore. 0aHistoric preservationxSocial aspectszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aUrban renewalzMarylandzBaltimore. 0aUrban renewalzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aHistoric Preservation.  agentrification.  aneighborhood change.  aneighborhood policy.  aurban policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COM